			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">general group (not bard specific) heroic opportunity strategy<a name="71911"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 6 05 6:03 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>one thing that my regular groupmates and i have found is that group heroic opportunities, although desirable, are often times not as effective as our ho linking strategy.
<br />

<br />
first, we all are talking via skype, so timing isn't so much of an issue.  basically what we do is continually rotate our fast soloing ho's in a set order by calling our chain starts.
<br />

<br />
this has a couple of advantages.  the ho's are quick and executed rapidly (one person is not waiting on another to get the ho done or perform the next ability in the ho chain), so the group is getting at least some of the benefits of ho's and our dps and abilities are increased via the ho buffs and damage.
<br />

<br />
secondly, because the ho's are done so quickly, other players can still cast spells after the ho starting move is completed and the chain is locked to boost dps, heal, buff, or debuff as needed while the person who started the chain completes it.  we can also pause between our short ho chains as needed depending on the situation, so set classes aren't locked into casting the next ability on the ho wheel if they need to do something else.
<br />

<br />
thirdly, all players get to use both the benefits of their ho's and their other class-specific combat abilities without being tied so much to just completing the ho chain at the expense of their other class abilities/functions.
<br />

<br />
finally, constantly linking different heroics, casting all my bardly buffs/debuffs/attacks is quite exciting and fun (and certainly keeps me busy), so it's like a twist of a different sort.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
