			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Lineup - What are you using and how?<a name="73159"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 12 05 3:32 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>HO's (Heroic Opportunities) an an element to EQ2 that requires both timing and coordination to pull off.
<br />

<br />
First of all they arent hard to do at surface glance. In the middle of a fight tho? Think again. You always have the choice of completeting the HO or not, and you can do a group HO or allow a single char's HO to be triggered and completed depending on the circumstances.
<br />

<br />
Example: On the initial pull of a group of say.. 3 or 4, the tank might want to do an individual HO as his taunt is the main spell being cast. This works great if you are the healer cause once his HO is triggered and in progress you can cast heals, buffs or whatever without worrying about drawing aggro.
<br />

<br />
In the middle of a fight you might want the extra damage you get from an HO being triggered. Or, you might get a special buff or damage shield or power regen or whatever depending on the classes present in the group. If you are in a group of more than two people, knowing who should do the answering when an HO starter chain is triggered is where the finesse comes in. You will get different effects depending on the person answering.
<br />

<br />
Towards the end of the fight, a single character might cast a self HO if they have the extra power and can squeeze in a buff or extra damage as a result. This works great in the case of group members running out of power and being unable to answer the HO with their own spell.
<br />

<br />
HO's have added an element of both control and randomness to the game that makes it a bit more fun than just whaling away at Mob__001.
<br />

<br />
Dovewing</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
